<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Alfred E. Smith's 1928 presidential campaign was significant because:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">He won the presidency</option>
            <option letter="b">He was the first Catholic presidential nominee</option>
            <option letter="c">He supported Prohibition</option>
            <option letter="d">He was a Republican reformer</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Alfred E. Smith's 1928 Democratic presidential campaign was historic as he was the first Catholic nominee of a major party. His campaign revealed persistent anti-Catholic prejudice in American society, as his religion, along with his opposition to Prohibition and urban background, led to significant opposition, particularly in rural Protestant areas. He lost decisively to Herbert Hoover.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
